<subSubSection pageId="4" pageNumber="595" type="etymology">
<paragraph blockId="4.[151,1437,260,968]" pageId="4" pageNumber="595">
<emphasis bold="true" box="[199,334,836,861]" pageId="4" pageNumber="595">Etymology.</emphasis>
The new species name is a Latin word, meaning fish tail, referring to the shape of the apeX of the aedeagus.
</paragraph>
</subSubSection>
<subSubSection pageId="4" pageNumber="595" type="discussion">
<paragraph blockId="4.[151,1437,260,968]" pageId="4" pageNumber="595">
<emphasis bold="true" box="[199,315,908,933]" pageId="4" pageNumber="595">Remarks.</emphasis>
This species resembles 
<taxonomicName authority="Nielson" authorityName="Nielson" authorityYear="1991" box="[584,801,908,933]" class="Insecta" family="Cicadellidae" genus="Brasura" higherTaxonomySource="GBIF" kingdom="Animalia" order="Hemiptera" pageId="4" pageNumber="595" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="species" species="peditata">
<emphasis box="[584,707,908,933]" italics="true" pageId="4" pageNumber="595">B. peditata</emphasis>
Nielson
</taxonomicName>
but differs in having a dense row of spines on both sides of the aedeagal shaft and the apeX of the aedeagus fish tail shaped.
</paragraph>
</subSubSection>
